    <p class="text-gray-700">Soft, creamy cheeses like Brie, Camembert, or aged Gruyère create magical pairings with Pinot Noir's silky texture and moderate tannins. The wine's acidity cuts through the cheese's richness while complementing its earthy flavors. Avoid sharp cheddars or pungent blues that can overwhelm the wine's delicate fruit profile.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibered text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair Pinot Noir with spicy food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir works with mildly spiced dishes but struggles with intense heat that masks its subtle flavors. Try it with dishes featuring warm spices like cinnamon, allspice, or mild paprika rather than fiery chiles. Moroccan tagines with dried fruits or gently spiced Indian dishes like tandoori chicken can work beautifully when the spice level stays moderate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What vegetables pair best with Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Earthy vegetables like mushrooms, roasted beets, and caramelized onions create natural harmony with Pinot Noir's soil-driven character. Root vegetables such as carrots, parsnips, and sweet potatoes complement the wine's fruit-forward nature when roasted to develop their natural sugars. Avoid bitter vegetables like raw kale or Brussels sprouts that can clash with the wine's delicate structure.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Pinot Noir good for beginners learning food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, Pinot Noir is excellent for beginners because its moderate tannins and bright acidity make it forgiving with many foods. Its versatility with everything from salmon to mushroom risotto provides plenty of successful pairing opportunities to build confidence. The wine's food-friendly nature means fewer "wrong" choices compared to bold wines like Cabernet Sauvignon or Barolo.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing aged versus young Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Pinot Noir's bright fruit flavors pair well with lighter dishes like grilled fish or herb-roasted chicken, while aged Pinot Noir develops earthier, more complex flavors that complement richer preparations like braised short ribs or wild game. Older wines also handle stronger flavors better, including aged cheeses and truffle dishes that might overwhelm a young bottle's delicate fruit character.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve different foods with rosé versus red Pinot Noir?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir rosé calls for lighter fare like seafood, salads, and summer vegetables, while red Pinot Noir can handle heartier dishes with more substantial proteins. The rosé's crisp acidity and delicate flavor work beautifully with grilled shrimp or goat cheese tarts, whereas the red wine's deeper structure complements roasted poultry or mushroom-based dishes. Think seasonal cooking - rosé for spring and summer, red for fall and winter preparations.</p>
